    <section style="margin-bottom:2rem">
      <h2>What You Cannot Automate (Yet)</h2>
      <p>Intellectual honesty requires acknowledging the limits. Three things genuinely require humans in 2026:</p>
      <ul style="color:var(--md-sys-color-on-surface-variant);line-height:1.8">
        <li><strong>Relationship-driven enterprise sales.</strong> Large contracts (&gt;$50K ACV) still close through trust built over months of human interaction. AI can handle the pipeline, but the close requires presence.</li>
        <li><strong>Novel strategic decisions.</strong> AI is excellent at executing known playbooks. When you're doing something genuinely new — entering a new market, pivoting the product, deciding whether to raise — human judgment is still superior.</li>
        <li><strong>Community building.</strong> The authentic founder story, the Twitter presence, the conference talk. These are human signals that AI-generated content cannot replicate at the same authenticity level.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The zero-employee company does not eliminate the founder. It focuses the founder on the 20% of work that actually requires a human, and automates the 80% that does not.</p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-bottom:2rem">
      <h2>Start the Playbook</h2>
      <p>The full Mekong CLI toolkit is open source and free to use locally with your own LLM. The cloud RaaS platform adds hosted execution, mission history, and team features. See the <a href="/docs/guides/quickstart">quickstart guide</a> to install and run your first commands, or see <a href="/docs/pricing">pricing</a> for cloud credits.</p>
      <p>The zero-employee SaaS is not about being cheap. It is about being fast, lean, and structurally profitable from day one. The founders building this way are not cutting corners — they are building the most defensible businesses in the market.</p>
    </section>

